CHOLERA - HONG KONG (03)
=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D
[see
Cholera - Hong Kong 970513120612
Cholera - Hong Kong (02) 970515095358]
[1]
Date: Fri, 16 May 97 12:15:14 HKT
From: "Dr. Ann Koehler" <koehler@sco1.med.cuhk.edu.hk>
There have been eight confirmed cases of cholera and another two suspected
cases reported in the last week in Hong Kong. The strains have so far been
indistinguishable, [all] with resistance to commonly used drugs apart from
quinolones, suggesting a point source. While the media has suggested that
the source has been traced to contaminated chicken feet produced in a local
factory, this has not been confirmed yet, and not all patients have eaten
food from this factory.
Cholera is uncommon in Hong Kong, and previous outbreaks have been traced to
contaminated sea water in which live seafood was kept in restaurants. These
outbreaks tend to occur at the same time as heavy rains and flooding.
There are plenty of places in Hong Kong where food hygiene is substandard,
and the public health authorities have a daunting task in trying to locate
the source of this outbreak. It is to be hoped that the investigation will
be allowed to proceed scientifically and professionally rather than as a
knee-jerk response to pressure from the media.
--
Dr Ann Koehler
Prince of Wales Hospital
Hong Kong
<koehler@sco1.med.cuhk.edu.hk>
